# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albert-probst
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:albert-probst/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] She attended grammar school and high school in Ithaca, New York, United States, graduating in 1959.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] She then studied education, history and English language and literature in Marburg, Jugenheim an der Bergstraße and Frankfurt am Main and passed her first and second state examinations to become a teacher at secondary schools.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1962 she was accepted into the teaching profession and from 1975 to 1976 she worked in the school department of the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1986 to 1992, she was head of the Paul Hindemith Comprehensive School in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] After leaving the parliamentary group in the Bundestag of her own accord, she became involved in the SPD on a voluntary basis, particularly in the *Forum One World*, which deals with development policy issues.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] She also heads the Rhine-Main regional group of Transparency International.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] She is also involved as chairwoman of the Citoyen Foundation, which supports civic engagement and is particularly concerned with the artistic and aesthetic education of children and young people.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is the daughter of Tassilo Tröscher.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1972 to 1977, from 1981 to 1989 and in 1991 she was a city councillor of the city of Frankfurt am Main, and from 1992 to 1993 a full-time district councillor of the Kreis Offenbach.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] From November 1994 to October 2002, Tröscher was a member of the German Bundestag for two terms.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] In the 1994 Bundestag election, she entered parliament via the SPD state list, and in the 1998 Bundestag election she won the direct mandate in the constituency 144 (Odenwald).
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1994 to 2002, she was a member of the Committee on Economic Cooperation and Development and from 1996 to 2002, she was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on development policy.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is a member of GEW, AWO, Kinderschutzbund, Pro Familia and medico international.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1999 she became a member of the board of trustees and the administrative committee of Deutsche Stiftung für internationale Entwicklung (DSE) and a member of German Foundation for International Development.
[src:albert-probst/adelheid-d-tröscher] (DSE) and a member of German Agro Action.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Adolf Spies von Büllesheim was born in Haus Hall in Ratheim, district of Heinsberg, in North Rhine-Westphalia, property of the baronial Spies von Büllesheim family since the 18th century.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] He was the son of Egon Franz Freiherr Spies von Büllesheim and his wife Maria (born Freiin von Oer).
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After school in Erkelenz he studied German law and farming at universities in Cologne and in Bonn.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After university he worked as a farmer and a lawyer from 1960 to 1997.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Since 1952 Spies von Büllesheim was a member of the CDU political party.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1969 to 1972 he was mayor of Hückelhoven.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1972 to 1987 Spies von Büllesheim was member of the German Bundestag for Heinsberg.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Spies von Büllesheim was married to Gräfin Maria Immaculata (born Concha) von Mirbach-Harff, Freiin von Vittinghoff (1938–2002), and together they had six children.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] CDU Hückelhoven.de: Die CDU Hückelhoven trauert um ihren Ehrenvorsitzenden Dr.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller joined the CDU in 1945 and was later elected to the state executive of the CDU Rhineland.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller was a member of the German Bundestag from 1961 to 1987.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] He had always entered parliament via the North Rhine-Westphalia state list.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] The social policy expert was Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour from 1965 to 1969 and Deputy Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs from 1969 to September 1981.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] From 1981 to 1987 he was deputy chairman of the CDU/CSU parliamentary group in the Bundestag.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] Born in Holzhausen, Homberg, Schmidt became a mechanic at a coal mine, then in 1942 was drafted into the navy as a submarine mechanic.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] He was taken as a prisoner of war and released at the end of the war, returning to the pit.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] In 1947, he joined the Union of Mining and Energy (IG BE), and immediately won election to the works council at the mine.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] In 1949, he joined the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), and the following year he studied in Frankfurt.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] In 1951, Schmidt began working full-time for IG BE, as its Munich youth secretary, then he successively ran the union's offices in Breisgau and Gießen, before in 1965 he became head of the union's Hesse-Rhineland-Palatinate district, and also won election to its executive.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] In 1969, Schmidt was elected as the president of IG BE, on a platform of improving working conditions in coal mines, and preserving jobs in coal mining and at nuclear power stations.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] In 1971, he was additionally elected as president of the Miners' International Federation, and in 1972 he was elected as an SPD member of the Bundestag.
[src:albert-probst/adolf-schmidt] Schmidt stood down from his international post in 1984, as president of the IG BE in 1985, and from the Bundestag in 1987.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] It later emerged that she had become entangled, as an industry lobbyist, in the CDU donations scandal.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The prosecutors' office in Düsseldorf launched an investigation against her in respect of allegations involving serious fraud, false statements and tax evasion, but by 2007 she was seriously ill and the case was suspended.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] It was dropped in 2008 on account of Hürland-Büning's "permanent incapacity to deal with matters" (*"wegen dauernder Verhandlungsunfähigkeit der Angeklagten"*).
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Agnes Oleynik was born into a Roman Catholic family in Holsterhausen, a small town on the western fringes of Dorsten (into which it was formally subsumed in 1943), a mid-sized mining and industrial town north of Essen, a short distance to the east of the Dutch frontier and Nijmegen.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She was enrolled at the local Catholic school in 1932.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] War broke out when she was 13 and troops were stationed at the school: teaching immediately became more "irregular" (*"... sehr unregelmäßig"*), especially after the children were sent to take part in combined classes at one of the two nearby protestant schools.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She completed her schooling young, with others in her cohort, in the spring of 1940, and was conscripted into the Labour Service (*"Reichsarbeitsdienst"*).
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She was later sent to work in a munitions factory.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] After war ended, in May 1945, she worked as a volunteer nurse before moving on to complete an apprenticeship as a carer at the "Westfalia Welfare College" (*"Westfälische Wohlfahrtsschule"*) in Münster.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Sources are for the most part silent about her marriage, but by 1960, when she returned to the labour market, it was as Agnes Hürland, the mother of four or five children.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She was employed, till 1968, as a secretary / senior support worker (*"Chefassistentin"*) with an industrial business.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She worked for two years for the national labour agency.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] After that there were two years as a rehabilitation counsellor.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] There are also references to her having worked as an insurance and real-estate broker (*"Immobilienmaklerin"*) during the 1960s and / or early 1970s.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] By 1969 her marriage had ended in divorce: there is a mention of her husband having been affected by alcoholism.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] After a brief flirtation with the centre-left Social Democratic Party (SPD) – "because I confused 'social' with 'social democratic'" – Agnes Hürland-Büning joined the centre-right CDU in 1964.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She served as a local councillor in Dorsten between 1969 and 1975, taking a particular interest in social policy.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Her career as a national politician started only when she was.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Her inclusion on the CDU candidate list for North Rhine-Westphalia resulted, according to one unsympathetic source, from the party's introduction of gender quotas.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] As a result, she found herself elected to the Bundestag in 1972.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Nationally the election result was a close one, and many commentators were surprised when, following coalition negotiations, the SPD's Willy Brandt returned to power as Chancellor, while the CDU remained in opposition.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning became a member of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs, in which she took a particular interest in to the needs of the disabled.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Helmut Kohl took over as CDU party leader in 1973.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Apart from her committee work she maintained a low profile in the Bundestag.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Kohl nevertheless valued her as a loyal party stalwart and when, in 1982, power finally passed to the CDU, Chancellor Kohl appointed her as "party business leader" (*" Fraktions-Geschäftsführerin"*) in the chamber.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She became known for her humanity, warmth, and willingness to reach out and make informal alliances with members of rival parties.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Even so, evidence of her political impact was limited.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Described by colleagues and observers – sometimes admiringly and sometimes disparagingly – as "the mother of the CDU/CSU party Bundestag group", one underwhelmed commentator suggested that she was at her happiest when organising the annual early summer asparagus lunch for the CDU Bundestag faction.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Directly after the 1987 election Chancellor Kohl made Hürland-Büning his secretary of state for defence.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She had no great specialist knowledge of defence matters, but many felt that her human qualities more than compensated for a lack of technical expertise.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Her grandmotherly manner, on display when she visited young recruits and junior officers, provided a reassuring picture.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Indeed, her appointment found support not just within the governing coalition parties but also from the SPD which was the principal opposition party.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She was the first woman to hold the post.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She paid particular attention to the welfare of the junior ranks.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] One development that she oversaw was a pilot project for the recruitment of female soldiers (on a volunteer basis).
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She continued to enjoy a close political relationship with Helmut Kohl.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] In a prescient remark during a visit to the Knesset in Jerusalem she noted that if anyone could achieve German reunification, it was Helmut Kohl.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Commentators also note that her position within the Ministry of Defence meant that military contracts worth million of marks crossed Agnes Hürland-Büning's desk.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] 1990 was the year of German reunification, and the first general election of the newly unified country took place on 2 December 1990.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] By now approximately six months short of her sixty-fifth birthday, Hürland-Büning did not stand for re-election.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She accordingly retired from the Bundestag early in 1991, ahead of the new parliamentary session.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] She retired with her reputation in robust good order, awarded (among other honours) the Order of Merit (*"Große Bundesverdienstkreuz der Bundesrepublik"*) and the Order of Olga.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] However, the name of Agnes Hürland-Büning hit the headlines towards the end of that year in connection with the emerging CDU donations scandal: more details of her alleged involvement in those events, most of which dated back to 1992, appeared in Der Spiegel in January 2000.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning resigned her membership of the Weizsäcker Commission on 20 January 2000, a few days after the Spiegel piece appeared.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Her involvement in transferring members of the old East German People's Army to the Bundeswehr was also abruptly terminated when she was dismissed by means of a telephone call from Defences Minister Scharping.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] According to the report of a parliamentary committee of enquiry, after retiring from her position with the Ministry of Defence, Agnes Hürland-Büning concluded several high-value "dubious consultancy agreements".
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Just two of the agreements, those with Thyssen AG and Elf Aquitaine, yielded fees amounting to eight and a half or nine and a half million Marks.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] (Sources differ.) What she had to do for all this money never became entirely clear.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] However, investigators felt that this may have amounted, at best, to an incomplete explanation, especially given that eight years later the pipeline construction in question had never taken place, apparently for unrelated reasons.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators appear never fully to have plumbed the suspected depths of the so-called Leuna affair, which sources imply may have been focused not so much on the personal enrichment of top politicians as on the garnering of funds to cover the political expenses incurred by the CDU.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators felt that the massive fees received by Hürland-Büning were completely disproportionate to anything that she might have done to earn them.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] There was also widespread speculation that even if she had received the fees stated, it had never been intended that she should be the ultimate recipient.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The suspicion persisted that she had passed on the funds in the wider context of the Leuna affair and of the associated CDU donations scandal.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] One member of the parliamentary committee was Friedhelm Julius Beucher of the SPD.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] He described Hürland-Büning as a "living money-laundering system for the [Christian Democratic] Union (CDU).
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] I think the lady's involvement was as the suitcase carrier" (*eine "lebende Geldwaschanlage der Union.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Ich glaube, die Dame war als Kofferträgerin aktiv."*).
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] In the words of one commentator, the suspected contents of the suitcase were "black money for Kohl's black coffers" (*"schwarzes Geld für Kohls schwarze Kassen"*).
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Nevertheless, it was clear from much of the media comment that many suspected that Hürland-Büning had also enriched herself along the way.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigations by the prosecutors' office were followed by the issuance of charges in December 2003.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Once her consultancy activities had been defined as a business it became liable for substantial arrears of unpaid business tax to the municipality.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] During her final years, with the threat of legal sanctions hanging over her, and a new generation of leaders controlling the CDU, there are indications that Hürland-Büning felt abandoned by those who had previously been friends.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Her former mentor Helmut Kohl increasingly withdrew from public life after the CDU donations scandal became public, especially following the tragic death of his first wife in 2001.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Within the little town of Dorsten there emerges a sense, from some sources, that family members and remaining friends felt that the work she had been able to do for individual citizens with problems, for Dorsten businesses, and for the town more generally, were all too quickly forgotten.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Meanwhile, at her criminal trial matters took a new twist in September 2004 when her defence lawyer submitted a doctor's certificate attesting that the 78 year old defendant's deteriorating health meant that she was no longer sufficiently fit to enable a fair trial take place.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Although it would take more than three more years for the court to reach a final decision in respect of the medical evidence, it was becoming increasingly likely that Agnes Hürland-Büning would go to the grave unconvicted but without her name ever being cleared.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] That was indeed the position on 9 March 2009 when she died following a major operation.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Only her family and a small number of close friends were present at her burial.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Her parliamentary colleagues were represented by a wreath that arrived from the Bundestag.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Since then she has been commemorated each year by a further wreath, sent on All Saints' Day, and decorated with the black/red/gold sash of the CDU/CSU, on behalf of her Bundestag former party colleagues and their successors in Berlin.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2011 insolvency proceedings were launched against the estate of Agnes Hürland-Büning in respect of around €200,000 in unpaid business taxes payable to the municipality of Dorsten at the time of her death.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] By 2011 the debt had been reduced to around €170,000 by means of monthly payments of €1,000.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The city maintained its claim for the balance through the bankruptcy.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The business tax claim by the municipality had already been the subject of major disagreements within the council as far back as 2002.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] At that point CDU councillors, with their controlling majority, had agreed to a compromise deal with their high-profile debtor, freezing the debt and hoping, by means of the agreement, at least to secure monthly repayments of €1,000.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] SPD and Green Party councillors had opposed the settlement while the FDP councillors had abstained in the vote.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The CDU share of the votes in the local council election slipped below 50% in 2009, although they remained the largest single party, with 22 of the 44 council seats.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2012, during an interview concerning the state of municipal finances, a reporter asked the Dorsten town treasurer – another CDU councillor – about the prospects of recovering the unpaid business taxes of former CDU Bundestag member Agnes Hürland-Büning.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The treasurer declined to speculate on how much money would become available at the conclusion of the insolvency proceedings.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Bundesautobahn 31 runs parallel with the Dutch frontier, linking Emden in the north with Bottrop to the south.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The section passing to the west of Dorsten was completed and opened in 1989.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Between Junctions 37 and 38 there is an unmarked junction, without signage and without a junction number.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The unmarked junction was not included in the plans for the road, and only those with local knowledge are aware that it can be accessed by leaving or joining the Autobahn where maps and signs indicate a parking area ("Parkplatz Dorsten-Holsterhausen").
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The limited access junction only permits traffic to join the Autobahn in a southerly direction, towards Bottrop (and, indirectly, Bonn) or to leave the Autobahn travelling north (from Bottrop and, indirectly, Bonn).
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The rumour gained added traction after the name of the former secretary of state began to appear in press reports connecting her with the CDU donations scandal.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Der Spiegel gave it national coverage in 2000 and repeated it in 2002.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2009 the pupils in class 9a at the Gymnasium St.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Ursula (secondary school) undertook what turned out to be an award winning investigation into the origins of the *"Hürlandausfahrt"*.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Arnold Erwig, their politics teacher, admitted that at the outset he had always assumed the rumours were true.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Only a few were prepared to have their voices recorded.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The town council had indeed objected to the Autobahn plans which had specified a junction at the hamlet of Schembeck, to the north, and a junction at Dorsten-West, some distance to the south.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] The city father demanded an extra Autobahn junction, but without success.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] They then invoked their local representative in the Bundestag.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Through her relationship with Chancellor Kohl, it turned out that Agnes Hürland-Büning did enjoy more influence with the transport planners than might have been expected.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Even her lobbying powers were not sufficient to provide for a complete additional junction, but the unmarked junction, accessible through the parking area, represented a compromise for which the city council at the time was appreciative.
[src:albert-probst/agnes-hürland-büning] Those with the necessary local knowledge were able to save themselves time by using the "secret" junction: at the time that did indeed includes Agnes Hürland-Büning herself.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] Probst was born in Garching bei München, Upper Bavaria.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] After graduation in 1951 from the Maximilians Gymnasium in Munich, Probst took an agricultural apprenticeship.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] He then studied agricultural sciences at the Technical University of Munich, graduating in 1958 with a diploma as an agricultural engineer.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] In Munich, he served in the Catholic student group K.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] He then joined the agricultural civil service, working at the milk research institute at TU Munich.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] He left this institute in 1961, after completing research.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] He returned to TU Munich in 1963, after two years as an agriculture adviser in France, to work on a research project concerning population genetics.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] At this time he began to participate in municipal politics.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] Probst was deputy chair of the culture team of the Christian Socialist Union for many years.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] From 1960 to 1973 he belonged to the country of the circle day of the district of Munich.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] He was also a member of the Garching local council from 1966 until 1990.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] From 1969 to 1998 Probst was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] He was chair of the Committee on Development and Science from 1972 to 1976, and from 1976 to 1982 chaired the Committee on Research and Technology.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] Until 1982, he chaired the science development team and served as spokesperson for the Christian Socialist Union rural group.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] Probst was a directly selected delegate of the Munich/Freising constituency in the Bundestag.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] From 1991 to 1999 he represented Germany at parliamentary meetings of the Council of Europe, and at the European Union.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] On 4 October 1982 Probst became Parliamentary Secretary of State at the Federal Ministry for Research and Technology, in the federal government led by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] Here he advocated the early provision of computers in schools.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] He served until the Bundestag election in 1990, leaving government on 24 January 1991.
[src:albert-probst/albert-probst] Probst is married and has four children.
